# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aldolase-a
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aldolase-a/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] 1,3-Bisphosphoglycerate is the conjugate base of 1,3-bisphosphoglyceric acid.
[src:aldolase-a/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] It is phosphorylated at the number 1 and 3 carbons.
[src:aldolase-a/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The result of this phosphorylation gives 1,3BPG important biological properties such as the ability to donate a phosphate group to adenosine diphosphate (ADP) in order to form the energy storage molecule adenosine triphosphate (ATP).
[src:aldolase-a/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Compound C00118 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:aldolase-a/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Enzyme 1.2.1.12 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:aldolase-a/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Compound C00236 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:aldolase-a/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Enzyme 2.7.2.3 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:aldolase-a/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Compound C00197 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:aldolase-a/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] 1,3BPG is a macroergic metabolic intermediate in the glycolytic pathway.
[src:aldolase-a/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] It is created by the exergonic oxidation of the aldehyde in glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate.
[src:aldolase-a/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The result of this oxidation is the conversion of the aldehyde group into a carboxylic acid group which drives the formation of an acyl phosphate bond.
[src:aldolase-a/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The latter reaction is the only step in the glycolytic pathway in which NAD+ is converted into NADH.
[src:aldolase-a/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The formation reaction of 1,3BPG requires the presence of an enzyme called glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate dehydrogenase.
[src:aldolase-a/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The high-energy acyl phosphate bond of 1,3BPG is important in respiration as it assists in the formation of ATP.
[src:aldolase-a/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The molecule of ATP created during the following reaction is the first molecule produced during respiration.
[src:aldolase-a/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The transfer of an inorganic phosphate from the carboxyl group on 1,3BPG to ADP to form ATP is reversible due to a low ΔG.
[src:aldolase-a/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] This is as a result of one acyl phosphate bond being cleaved whilst another is created.
[src:aldolase-a/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] This reaction is not naturally spontaneous and requires the presence of a catalyst.
[src:aldolase-a/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] This role is performed by the enzyme phosphoglycerate kinase.
[src:aldolase-a/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] During the reaction phosphoglycerate kinase undergoes a substrate induced conformational change similar to another metabolic enzyme called hexokinase.
[src:aldolase-a/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Because two molecules of glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate are formed during glycolysis from one molecule of glucose, 1,3BPG can be said to be responsible for two of the ten molecules of ATP produced during the entire process.
[src:aldolase-a/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Glycolysis also uses two molecules of ATP in its initial stages as a committed and irreversible step.
[src:aldolase-a/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] For this reason glycolysis is not reversible and has a net produce of 2 molecules of ATP and two of NADH.
[src:aldolase-a/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The two molecules of NADH themselves go on to produce approximately 3 molecules of ATP each.
[src:aldolase-a/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] 1,3-BPG has a very similar role in the Calvin cycle to its role in the glycolytic pathway.
[src:aldolase-a/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] For this reason both reactions are said to be analogous.
[src:aldolase-a/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] However the reaction pathway is effectively reversed.
[src:aldolase-a/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The only other major difference between the two reactions is that NADPH is used as an electron donor in the calvin cycle whilst NAD+ is used as an electron acceptor in glycolysis.
[src:aldolase-a/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] In this reaction cycle 1,3BPG originates from 3-phosphoglycerate and is made into glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate by the action of specific enzymes.
[src:aldolase-a/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Contrary to the similar reactions of the glycolytic pathway, 1,3BPG in the Calvin cycle does not produce ATP but instead uses it.
[src:aldolase-a/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] For this reason it can be considered to be an irreversible and committed step in the cycle.
[src:aldolase-a/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The outcome of this section of the cycle is an inorganic phosphate is removed from 1,3BPG as a hydrogen ion and two electrons are added to the compound+.
[src:aldolase-a/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] In complete reverse of the glycolytic pathway reaction, the enzyme phosphoglycerate kinase catalyses the reduction of the carboxyl group of 1,3BPG to form an aldehyde instead.
[src:aldolase-a/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] This reaction also releases an inorganic phosphate molecule which is subsequently used as energy for the donation of electrons from the conversion of NADPH to NADP+.
[src:aldolase-a/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Overseeing this latter stage of the reaction is the enzyme glyceraldehyde-phosphate dehydrogenase.
[src:aldolase-a/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] During normal metabolism in human erythrocytes, ≈19% of the 1,3BPG produced does not go any further in the glycolytic pathway.
[src:aldolase-a/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] It is instead shunted through the Luebering–Rapoport pathway involving the reduction of ATP in the red blood cells.
[src:aldolase-a/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] During this alternate pathway it is made into a similar molecule called 2,3-bisphosphoglyceric acid (2,3BPG).
[src:aldolase-a/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] 2,3BPG is used as a mechanism to oversee the efficient release of oxygen from hemoglobin.
[src:aldolase-a/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Levels of this 1,3BPG will raise in a patient's blood when oxygen levels are low as this is one of the mechanisms of acclimatization.
[src:aldolase-a/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Low oxygen levels trigger a rise in 1,3BPG levels which in turn raises the level of 2,3BPG which alters the efficiency of oxygen dissociation from hemoglobin.
[src:aldolase-a/2-hydroxyphytanoyl-coa-lyase] It requires thiamine diphosphate (ThDP) as cofactor.
[src:aldolase-a/2-hydroxyphytanoyl-coa-lyase] The entry is intended to mainly represent the class of enzymes examplified by human HACL1 (gene), which can catalyze both reactions and is found in the peroxisome.
[src:aldolase-a/2-hydroxyphytanoyl-coa-lyase] It is required for handling phytanic acid.
[src:aldolase-a/2-hydroxyphytanoyl-coa-lyase] Humans and other mammals have another similar enzymes that only catalyzes reaction (2) and is instead located in the endoplasmic reticulum, HACL2 (gene).
[src:aldolase-a/2-hydroxyphytanoyl-coa-lyase] This one participates in phytosphingosine degradation.
[src:aldolase-a/2-hydroxyphytanoyl-coa-lyase] Both the baker's yeast and the fission yeast have a *Pxp1* gene corresponding to this activity, as annotated on UniProt by sequence similarity (not by experimental characterization of enzyme activity).
[src:aldolase-a/2-hydroxyphytanoyl-coa-lyase] These two versions are known to appear in the cytoplasm and the peroxisome based on experimental evidence listed in UniProt.
[src:aldolase-a/2-hydroxyphytanoyl-coa-lyase] Both the mouse-ear cress (Arath) and the rice have a *HACL* gene corresponding to this activity, as annotated on UniProt by sequence similarity (not by experimental characterization of enzyme activity).
[src:aldolase-a/2-hydroxyphytanoyl-coa-lyase] The Arath version is experimentally detected in the cytoplasm, peroxisome, and plastid.
[src:aldolase-a/2-hydroxyphytanoyl-coa-lyase] UniProt reports that the social ameoba *Dictyostelium discoideum* has a version of this enzyme, as annotated on UniProt by sequence similarity (not by experimental characterization of enzyme activity).
[src:aldolase-a/2-phosphoglyceric-acid] 2-phosphoglyceric acid is an intermediate that is part of the glycolysis pathway, and it is converted into phosphoenolpyruvate (PEP) by an enolase.
[src:aldolase-a/2-phosphoglyceric-acid] There are three types of enolase enzymes that are able to catalyze the conversion of 2-phosphoglyceric acid into PEP, which are alpha-enolase, beta-enolase, and gamma-enolase.
[src:aldolase-a/2-phosphoglyceric-acid] Studies have found that Alpha-enolase is the most common enolase, so it is often the specific enolase used to convert 2-phosphoglyceric acid into PEP.
[src:aldolase-a/2-phosphoglyceric-acid] Alpha-enolase catalyzes this conversion process by acting as a Hydrolase, which means that alpha-enolase removes a water molecule from the 2-phosphoglyceric acid in order to form PEP.
[src:aldolase-a/2-phosphoglyceric-acid] Enzyme 5.4.2.1 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:aldolase-a/2-phosphoglyceric-acid] Compound C00631 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:aldolase-a/2-phosphoglyceric-acid] Enzyme 4.2.1.11 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:aldolase-a/2-phosphoglyceric-acid] Compound C00074 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:aldolase-a/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] The HMGCL gene encodes a 34.5-kDa protein that is localized to the mitochondrion and peroxisome.
[src:aldolase-a/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] Multible isoforms of the proteins are known due to alternative splicing.
[src:aldolase-a/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] The major isoform (isoform 1) is most highly expressed in the liver whereas isoform 2 is found in energy-demanding tissues including the brain, heart, and skeletal muscle.
[src:aldolase-a/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] Structure of the HMGCL protein has been resolved by X-ray crystallography at 2.1-Å resolution, and reveals that the protein may function as a dimer.
[src:aldolase-a/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] Substrate access to the active site of the HMGCL enzyme involves substrate binding across a cavity located at the C-terminal end of a beta barrel structure.
[src:aldolase-a/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] In addition, the lysine 48 residue which is mutated in patients with 3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-CoA lyase deficiency is also found to be necessary for substrate binding.
[src:aldolase-a/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] Electron density was observed indicating a bound metal ion, presumably Mg2+ due to its inclusion in the crystallization medium.
[src:aldolase-a/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] The enzyme activity is dependent on the presence of the metal this was determined by mutating His233 to Ala233 and Asp42 to Asn42 and experiencing catalytic deficiency of 6.4E−3 kcat/kM and 1.3E−5 kcat/kM respectively.
[src:aldolase-a/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] The substrate binding site includes arginine 41 making a salt bridge to the carboxylate of the hydroxyglutaric acid closest to metal ion.
[src:aldolase-a/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] A mutation in Arg 41 results in a drastic decrease of catalytic activity.
[src:aldolase-a/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] The extreme decrease in efficiency suggests the direct involvement in the chemistry of the catalytic reaction.
[src:aldolase-a/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] This Arg41 also salt bridges to Glu72 to fold into the correct position and charge balance Arg41 to bind to the substrate.
[src:aldolase-a/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] The HMGCL protein plays an essential role in breaking down dietary proteins and fats for energy.
[src:aldolase-a/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] and requires a divalent metal ion as co-factor.
[src:aldolase-a/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] Deficiency HMG-CoA lyase deficiency causes hypoketotic hypoglycemia similar to that is caused by HMGCS2 mutations but also leads to organic acid accumulation and metabolic acidosis due to altered leucine metabolism.
[src:aldolase-a/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] This disorder can be mistaken for Reye syndrome because of the symptoms of vomiting, lethargy, and convulsions.
[src:aldolase-a/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] Mutations in the *HMGCL* gene cause 3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-CoA lyase deficiency (HMGCLD), a rare autosomal recessive inborn error of metabolism characterized by disruption of ketogenesis and L-leucine catabolism.
[src:aldolase-a/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] To-date more than 30 different mutations including missense mutations of different residues have been associated with patients with HMGCLD in diverse families and ethnicities.
[src:aldolase-a/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] HMGCLD typically presents in the first year of the patient's life after a fasting period.
[src:aldolase-a/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] Clinical acute symptoms include vomiting, seizures, metabolic acidosis, hypoketotic hypoglycemia, and lethargy.
[src:aldolase-a/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] HMGCL interacts with itself to form homodimers and homotetramers.
[src:aldolase-a/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] It is also shown in yeast two-hybrid experiments to interact with DNAJA1.
[src:aldolase-a/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] In the glycolytic pathway, 1,3-bisphosphoglycerate is dephosphorylated to form 3-phosphoglyceric acid in a coupled reaction producing two ATP via substrate-level phosphorylation.
[src:aldolase-a/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] The single phosphate group left on the 3-PGA molecule then moves from an end carbon to a central carbon, producing 2-phosphoglycerate.
[src:aldolase-a/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] This phosphate group relocation is catalyzed by phosphoglycerate mutase, an enzyme that also catalyzes the reverse reaction.
[src:aldolase-a/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] In the light-independent reactions (also known as the Calvin-Benson cycle), two 3-phosphoglycerate molecules are synthesized.
[src:aldolase-a/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] RuBP, a 5-carbon sugar, undergoes carbon fixation, catalyzed by the rubisco enzyme, to become an unstable 6-carbon intermediate.
[src:aldolase-a/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] This intermediate is then cleaved into two, separate 3-carbon molecules of 3-PGA.
[src:aldolase-a/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] G3P eventually reacts to form the sugars such as glucose or fructose or more complex starches.
[src:aldolase-a/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] Glycerate 3-phosphate (formed from 3-phosphoglycerate) is also a precursor for serine, which, in turn, can create cysteine and glycine through the homocysteine cycle.
[src:aldolase-a/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] 3-phosphoglycerate can be separated and measured using paper chromatography as well as with column chromatography and other chromatographic separation methods.
[src:aldolase-a/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] It can be identified using both gas-chromatography and liquid-chromatography mass spectrometry and has been optimized for evaluation using tandem MS techniques.
[src:aldolase-a/5] The relative positions of structures along strands of nucleic acid, including genes and various protein binding sites, are usually noted as being either *upstream* (towards the 5′-end) or *downstream* (towards the 3′-end).
[src:aldolase-a/5] Directionality is related to, but different from, sense.
[src:aldolase-a/5] Transcription of single-stranded RNA from a double-stranded DNA template requires the selection of one strand of the DNA template as the template strand that directly interacts with the nascent RNA due to complementary sequence.
[src:aldolase-a/5] The other strand is not copied directly, but necessarily its sequence will be similar to that of the RNA.
[src:aldolase-a/5] Transcription initiation sites generally occur on both strands of an organism's DNA, and specify the location, direction, and circumstances under which transcription will occur.
[src:aldolase-a/5] If the transcript encodes one or (rarely) more proteins, translation of each protein by the ribosome will proceed in a 5′-to-3′ direction, and will extend the protein from its N-terminus toward its C-terminus.
[src:aldolase-a/5] For example, in a typical gene a start codon (5′-ATG-3′) is a DNA sequence within the sense strand.
[src:aldolase-a/5] Transcription begins at an upstream site (relative to the sense strand), and as it proceeds through the region it copies the 3′-TAC-5′ from the template strand to produce 5′-AUG-3′ within a messenger RNA (mRNA).
[src:aldolase-a/5] The mRNA is scanned by the ribosome from the 5′ end, where the start codon directs the incorporation of a methionine (bacteria, mitochondria, and plastids use *N*-formylmethionine instead) at the N terminus of the protein.
[src:aldolase-a/5] By convention, single strands of DNA and RNA sequences are written in a 5′-to-3′ direction except as needed to illustrate the pattern of base pairing.
[src:aldolase-a/5] The 5′-end (pronounced "five prime end") designates the end of the DNA or RNA strand that has the fifth carbon in the sugar-ring of the deoxyribose or ribose at its terminus.
[src:aldolase-a/5] A phosphate group attached to the 5′-end permits ligation of two nucleotides, i.e., the covalent binding of a 5′-phosphate to the 3′-hydroxyl group of another nucleotide, to form a phosphodiester bond.
[src:aldolase-a/5] Removal of the 5′-phosphate prevents ligation.
[src:aldolase-a/5] To prevent unwanted nucleic acid ligation (e.g. self-ligation of a plasmid vector in DNA cloning), molecular biologists commonly remove the 5′-phosphate with a phosphatase.
[src:aldolase-a/5] The 5′-end of nascent messenger RNA is the site at which post-transcriptional capping occurs, a process which is vital to producing mature messenger RNA.
[src:aldolase-a/5] Capping increases the stability of the messenger RNA while it undergoes translation, providing resistance to the degradative effects of exonucleases.
[src:aldolase-a/5] It consists of a methylated nucleotide (methylguanosine) attached to the messenger RNA in a rare 5′- to 5′-triphosphate linkage.
[src:aldolase-a/5] The 5′-*flanking* region of a gene often denotes a region of DNA which is not transcribed into RNA.
[src:aldolase-a/5] The 5′-flanking region contains the gene promoter, and may also contain enhancers or other protein binding sites.
[src:aldolase-a/5] The 5′-*untranslated* region (5′-UTR) is a region of a gene which is transcribed into mRNA, and is located at the 5′-end of the mRNA.
[src:aldolase-a/5] This region of an mRNA may or may not be translated, but is usually involved in the regulation of translation.
[src:aldolase-a/5] The 5′-untranslated region is the portion of the DNA starting from the cap site and extending to the base just before the AUG translation initiation codon of the main coding sequence.
[src:aldolase-a/5] This region may have sequences, such as the ribosome binding site and Kozak sequence, which determine the translation efficiency of the mRNA, or which may affect the stability of the mRNA.
[src:aldolase-a/5] The 3′-end (three prime end) of a strand is so named due to it terminating at the hydroxyl group of the third carbon in the sugar-ring, and is known as the *tail end*.
[src:aldolase-a/5] The 3′-hydroxyl is necessary in the synthesis of new nucleic acid molecules as it is ligated (joined) to the 5′-phosphate of a separate nucleotide, allowing the formation of strands of linked nucleotides.
[src:aldolase-a/5] Molecular biologists can use nucleotides that lack a 3′-hydroxyl (dideoxyribonucleotides) to interrupt the replication of DNA.
[src:aldolase-a/5] This technique is known as the dideoxy chain-termination method or the Sanger method, and is used to determine the order of nucleotides in DNA.
[src:aldolase-a/5] The 3′-end of nascent messenger RNA is the site of post-transcriptional polyadenylation, which attaches a chain of 50 to 250 adenosine residues to produce mature messenger RNA.
[src:aldolase-a/5] This chain helps in determining how long the messenger RNA lasts in the cell, influencing how much protein is produced from it.
[src:aldolase-a/5] The 3′-*flanking* region is a region of DNA that is not copied into the mature mRNA, but which is present adjacent to 3′-end of the gene.
[src:aldolase-a/5] It was originally thought that the 3′-flanking DNA was not transcribed at all, but it was discovered to be transcribed into RNA and quickly removed during processing of the primary transcript to form the mature mRNA.
[src:aldolase-a/5] The 3′-flanking region often contains sequences that affect the formation of the 3′-end of the message.
[src:aldolase-a/5] It may also contain enhancers or other sites to which proteins may bind.
[src:aldolase-a/5] The 3′-*untranslated* region (3′-UTR) is a region of the DNA which *is* transcribed into mRNA and becomes the 3′-end of the message, but which does not contain protein coding sequence.
[src:aldolase-a/5] Everything between the stop codon and the polyA tail is considered to be 3′-untranslated.
[src:aldolase-a/5] The 3′-untranslated region may affect the translation efficiency of the mRNA or the stability of the mRNA.
[src:aldolase-a/5] It also has sequences which are required for the addition of the poly(A) tail to the message, including the hexanucleotide AAUAAA.
[src:aldolase-a/aldolase-a] The protein encoded by this gene is a glycolytic enzyme that catalyzes the reversible conversion of fructose-1,6-bisphosphate to glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate (G3P) and dihydroxyacetone phosphate (DHAP).
[src:aldolase-a/aldolase-a] Three aldolase isozymes (A, B, and C), encoded by three different genes, are differentially expressed during development.
[src:aldolase-a/aldolase-a] Aldolase A is found in the developing embryo and is produced in even greater amounts in adult muscle.
[src:aldolase-a/aldolase-a] Aldolase A expression is repressed in adult liver, kidney and intestine and similar to aldolase C levels in brain and other nervous tissue.
[src:aldolase-a/aldolase-a] Aldolase A deficiency has been associated with myopathy and hemolytic anemia.
[src:aldolase-a/aldolase-a] Alternative splicing and alternative promoter usage results in multiple transcript variants.
[src:aldolase-a/aldolase-a] Related pseudogenes have been identified on chromosomes 3 and 10.
[src:aldolase-a/aldolase-a] ALDOA is a homotetramer and one of the three aldolase isozymes (A, B, and C), encoded by three different genes.
[src:aldolase-a/aldolase-a] The *ALDOA* gene contains 8 exons and the 5' UTR IB.
[src:aldolase-a/aldolase-a] Key amino acids responsible for its catalytic function have been identified.
[src:aldolase-a/aldolase-a] The residue Tyr363 functions as the acid–base catalyst for protonating C3 of the substrate, while Lys146 is proposed to stabilize the negative charge of the resulting conjugate base of Tyr363 and the strained configuration of the C-terminal.
[src:aldolase-a/aldolase-a] Residue Glu187 participates in multiple functions, including FBP aldolase catalysis, acid–base catalysis during substrate binding, dehydration, and substrate cleavage.
[src:aldolase-a/aldolase-a] Though ALDOA localizes to the nucleus, it lacks any known nuclear localization signals (NLS).
[src:aldolase-a/aldolase-a] In mammalian aldolase, the key catalytic amino acid residues involved in the reaction are lysine and tyrosine.
[src:aldolase-a/aldolase-a] The tyrosine acts as an efficient hydrogen acceptor while the lysine covalently binds and stabilizes the intermediates.
[src:aldolase-a/aldolase-a] Many bacteria use two magnesium ions in place of the lysine.
[src:aldolase-a/aldolase-a] Compound C05378 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:aldolase-a/aldolase-a] Enzyme 4.1.2.13 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:aldolase-a/aldolase-a] Compound C00111 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:aldolase-a/aldolase-a] ALDOA is a key enzyme in the fourth step of glycolysis, as well as in the reverse pathway gluconeogenesis.
[src:aldolase-a/aldolase-a] It catalyzes the reversible conversion of fructose-1,6-bisphosphate to glyceraldehydes-3-phosphate and dihydroxyacetone phosphate by aldol cleavage of the C3–C4 bond.
[src:aldolase-a/aldolase-a] As a result, it is a crucial player in ATP biosynthesis.
[src:aldolase-a/aldolase-a] ALDOA also contributes to other "moonlighting" functions such as muscle maintenance, regulation of cell shape and motility, striated muscle contraction, actin cytoskeleton organization, and regulation of cell proliferation.
[src:aldolase-a/aldolase-a] ALDOA likely regulates actin cytoskeleton remodeling through interacting with cytohesin-2 (ARNO) and Arf6.
[src:aldolase-a/aldolase-a] ALDOA is ubiquitously expressed in most tissues, though it is predominantly expressed in developing embryo and adult muscle.
[src:aldolase-a/aldolase-a] In lymphocytes, ALDOA is the predominant aldolase isoform.
[src:aldolase-a/aldolase-a] Within the cell, ALDOA typically localizes to the cytoplasm, but it can localize to the nucleus during DNA synthesis of the cell cycle S phase.
[src:aldolase-a/aldolase-a] This nuclear localization is regulated by the protein kinases AKT and p38.
[src:aldolase-a/aldolase-a] It is suggested that the nucleus serves as a reservoir for ALDOA in low glucose conditions.
[src:aldolase-a/aldolase-a] ALDOA has also been found in mitochondria.
[src:aldolase-a/aldolase-a] ALDOA is regulated by the energy metabolism substrates glucose, lactate, and glutamine.
[src:aldolase-a/aldolase-a] In human mast cells (MCs), ALDOA has been observed to undergo post-translational regulation by protein tyrosine nitration, which may alter its relative affinity for FBP and/or IP3.
[src:aldolase-a/aldolase-a] This change then affects IP3 and PLC signaling cascades in IgE-dependent responses.
[src:aldolase-a/aldolase-a] Aldolase A (ALDOA) is highly expressed in multiple cancers, including lung squamous cell carcinoma (LSCC), renal cancer, and hepatocellular carcinoma.
[src:aldolase-a/aldolase-a] It is proposed that ALDOA overexpression enhances glycolysis in these tumor cells, promoting their growth.
[src:aldolase-a/aldolase-a] In LSCC, its upregulation correlates with metastasis and poor prognosis, while its downregulation reduces tumor cell motility and tumorigenesis.
[src:aldolase-a/aldolase-a] Thus, ALDOA could be a potential LSCC biomarker and therapeutic drug target.
[src:aldolase-a/aldolase-a] Aldolase A deficiency is a rare, autosomal recessive disorder that is linked to hemolysis and accompanied by weakness, muscle pain, and myopathy.
